//purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the wide interest in material culture, art, and aesthetics, few studies have considered them in light of the importance of the social imagination - the complex ways in which we conceptualize our social surroundings. This collection engages the “material turn” in the arts, humanities, and social sciences through a range of original contributions on creativity in diverse global and contemporary social settings. The authors engage with everyday objects, art, rituals, and ethnographic exhibitions to analyze the relationship between material culture and the social imagination. What results is a better understanding of how the material embodies and influences our idea of the social world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCreative ability. 0aImagination. 0aMaterial culturexSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBjerregaard, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruland, Stine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesai, Amit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuglerud, Øivind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuglerud, Øivind, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKasprycki, Sylvia S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuldova, Tereza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagowan, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaguib, Saphinaz-Amal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerminow, Arne Aleksej, econtributor.4ctb4h